# Administration — Quality Assurance & Audit (QA)

## Purpose

Quality Assurance exists to protect:
- Scene consistency
- Medical realism
- Fairness across all players
- Department professionalism

QA is not punishment.

QA exists to improve performance, prevent drift, and maintain standards.

---

## Philosophy

We correct patterns, not single mistakes.

A single imperfect scene is training.
Repeated issues become supervision.
Intentional abuse becomes discipline.

QA builds stronger providers.

---

## Scope of Review

Supervisors and Command may review:

- Patient Care Reports (PCRs)
- Bodycam footage (if available)
- Radio logs
- Major incident scenes
- High-conflict or disputed outcomes
- Death pronouncements
- Medical holds
- Life Flight activations

Reviews may be random or triggered by complaint.

---

## Random Audit Program

Supervisors SHOULD conduct periodic audits.

Recommended:
- 2–3 PCR reviews per week
- At least one trauma case
- At least one refusal (RMA) case

Random audits prevent favoritism and maintain fairness.

---

## What QA Looks For

### 1. Scene Safety
- Proper staging
- Code 4 compliance
- Disengagement during active gunfire
- No unsafe hero entries

### 2. Medical Realism
- Injury severity matches mechanism
- No “magic fixes”
- Proper use of transport decisions
- Consistent application of Decision Trees

### 3. Scope Compliance
- Provider stayed within scope
- Proper escalation to Paramedic/AMU when required

### 4. Documentation Quality
- PCR completeness
- Clear assessment and treatment notes
- Proper RMA documentation
- Death pronouncements justified

### 5. Radio Discipline
- Clear, concise transmissions
- No arguing on radio
- Proper escalation to Command when needed

---

## Pattern Review System

If QA identifies a pattern:

Step 1 — Informal Coaching  
Step 2 — Documented Counseling  
Step 3 — Retraining Requirement  
Step 4 — Discipline (if continued or intentional)

QA escalates based on frequency and severity.

---

## Immediate Review Triggers

The following automatically trigger Command review:

- Questionable survivability decisions
- Multiple severe trauma cases involving same provider
- Death pronouncement disputes
- Unauthorized aircraft use
- Allegations of powergaming via medical systems
- PCR falsification concerns

---

## Protection Against Abuse

QA MUST NOT be used to:
- Target specific members unfairly
- Punish personality conflicts
- Override good-faith medical judgment without evidence

Command must document rationale for any corrective action.

---

## Feedback Process

Members MAY request feedback on:
- Complex scenes
- Disputed outcomes
- Career progression readiness

Supervisors SHOULD provide constructive feedback within 72 hours when requested.

---

## Transparency Rule

Members subject to QA review MUST:
- Be informed of findings
- Be told if retraining is required
- Be informed if discipline is recommended

There are no secret discipline systems.

---

## Goal

The goal of QA is simple:

Consistency.
Professionalism.
Balanced realism.
Department strength.

A strong QA system builds a strong department.
